33 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 7B-201(a) reads as rewritten:
34 "(a) When the court obtains jurisdiction over a juvenile, jurisdiction shall continue until
35 terminated by order of the court or until the juvenile reaches the age of 18 years or is otherwise
36 emancipated, or upon the juvenile's death, whichever occurs first."
37 SECTION 2.(b) This section is effective when it becomes law and applies to any
38 action pending or filed on or after that date.
39 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 7B-302 reads as rewritten:
40 "§ 7B-302. Assessment by director; military affiliation; access to confidential information;
41 notification of person making the report.
42 (a) When a report of abuse, neglect, or dependency is received, the director of the
43 department of social services shall make a prompt and thorough assessment, using either a family
44 assessment response or an investigative assessment response, in order to ascertain the facts of the
45 case, including collecting information concerning the military affiliation of the parent, guardian,
46 custodian, or caretaker of the juvenile alleged to have been abused or neglected, the extent of the
47 abuse or neglect, and the risk of harm to the juvenile, in order to determine whether protective
48 services should be provided or the complaint filed as a petition. When the report alleges abuse,
49 the director shall immediately, but no later than 24 hours after receipt of the report, initiate the
50 assessment. When the report alleges neglect or dependency, the director shall initiate the
51 assessment within 72 hours following receipt of the report. When the report alleges abandonment
Page 2 House Bill 612-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 of a juvenile or unlawful transfer of custody under G.S. 14-321.2, the director shall immediately
2 initiate an assessment. When the report alleges abandonment, the director shall also take
3 appropriate steps to assume temporary custody of the juvenile, and take appropriate steps to
4 secure an order for nonsecure custody of the juvenile. The assessment and evaluation shall
5 include a visit to the place where the juvenile resides, except when the report alleges abuse or
6 neglect in a child care facility as defined in Article 7 of Chapter 110 of the General Statutes.
7 When a report alleges abuse or neglect in a child care facility as defined in Article 7 of Chapter
8 110 of the General Statutes, a visit to the place where the juvenile resides is not required. When
9 the report alleges abandonment, the assessment shall include a request from the director to law
10 enforcement officials to investigate through the North Carolina Center for Missing Persons and
11 other national and State resources whether the juvenile is a missing child.
12 …
13 (c) If the assessment indicates that abuse, neglect, or dependency has occurred, the
14 director shall decide whether immediate removal of the juvenile or any other juveniles in the
15 home is necessary for their protection. If immediate removal does not seem necessary, the
16 director shall immediately provide or arrange for protective services. If the parent, guardian,
17 custodian, or caretaker refuses to accept the protective services provided or arranged by the
18 director, the director shall sign a petition seeking and if the legal counsel for the department has
19 not also signed the petition, the director shall attest that the petition has been reviewed by the
20 legal counsel for the department. The petition shall allege the applicable facts to invoke the
21 jurisdiction of the court for the protection of the juvenile or juveniles.
22 (d) If immediate removal seems necessary for the protection of the juvenile or other
23 juveniles in the home, the director shall sign a petition that alleges and if the legal counsel for the
24 department has not also signed the petition, the director shall attest that the petition has been
25 reviewed by the legal counsel for the department. The petition shall allege the applicable facts to
26 invoke the jurisdiction of the court. Where the assessment shows that it is warranted, a protective
27 services worker may assume temporary custody of the juvenile for the juvenile's protection
28 pursuant to Article 5 of this Chapter.
29 (d1) Whenever a juvenile is removed from the home of a parent, guardian, custodian,
30 stepparent, or adult relative entrusted with the juvenile's care due to physical abuse, the director
31 shall conduct a thorough review of the background of the alleged abuser or abusers. This review
32 shall include a criminal history check and a review of any available mental health records. If the
33 review reveals that the alleged abuser or abusers have a history of violent behavior against people,
34 the director shall petition the court to order the alleged abuser or abusers to submit to a complete
35 mental health evaluation by a licensed psychologist or psychiatrist.
36 …
37 (f) Within five working days after receipt of the report of abuse, neglect, or dependency,
38 the director shall give written notice to the person making the report, unless requested by that
39 person not to give notice, as to whether the report was accepted for assessment assessment, the
40 basis for that decision, and whether the report was referred to the appropriate State or local law
41 enforcement agency. In the event the director decides not to accept the report for an assessment,
42 the person making the report shall be informed in writing of the procedures necessary to request
43 a review by the Division of the director's decision. A request for review shall be made within five
44 working days of receipt of the written notification. The Division shall review the director's
45 decision within five working days of receiving a request for review and may affirm the decision
46 or direct the department to initiate an assessment of the report. Nothing in this section shall
47 prevent the person making the report from requesting a review by the director of the department
48 and from the director conducting such a review.
49 (g) Within five working days after completion of the protective services assessment, the
50 director shall give subsequent written notice to the person making the report, unless requested by
51 that person not to give notice, as to whether there is a finding of abuse, neglect, or dependency,
