9 Division shall notify the person making the report and the director of the time and place for the
10 review, and the director shall immediately transmit to the prosecutor Division a copy of a
11 summary of the assessment."
12 SECTION 20.(b) G.S. 7B-306 reads as rewritten:
13 "§ 7B-306. Review by prosecutor.Division.
14 (a) The prosecutor Division shall review the director's determination that a petition
15 should not be filed within 20 days after the person making the report is notified. receipt of a
16 request for review is made in accordance with G.S. 7B-305. The review shall include conferences
17 with the person making the report, the protective services worker, the juvenile, if practicable, and
18 other persons known to have pertinent information about the juvenile or the juvenile's family.
19 (b) At the conclusion of the conferences, review the prosecutor Division may affirm take
20 any of the following actions:
21 (1) Affirm the decision made by the director, may request director.
22 (2) Request the appropriate local law enforcement agency to investigate the
23 allegations, or may direct allegations.
24 (3) Direct the director to take a specific action to provide protective services or
25 file a petition."
26 SECTION 20.(c) G.S. 7B-308(b) reads as rewritten:
27 "(b) Immediately upon receipt of judicial authority to retain custody, the physician, the
28 administrator, or that person's designee shall so notify the director of social services for the
29 county in which the facility is located. The director shall treat this notification as a report of
30 suspected abuse and shall immediately begin an assessment of the case.
31 (1) If the assessment reveals (i) that it is the opinion of the certifying physician
32 that the juvenile is in need of medical treatment to cure or alleviate physical
33 distress or to prevent the juvenile from suffering serious physical injury, and
34 (ii) that it is the opinion of the physician that the juvenile should for these
35 reasons remain in the custody of the facility for 12 hours, but (iii) that the
36 juvenile's parent, guardian, custodian, or caretaker cannot be reached or, upon
37 request, will not consent to the treatment within the facility, the director shall
38 within the initial 12-hour period file a juvenile petition alleging abuse and
39 setting forth supporting allegations and shall seek a nonsecure custody order.
40 A petition filed and a nonsecure custody order obtained in accordance with
41 this subdivision shall come on for hearing under the regular provisions of this
42 Subchapter unless the director and the certifying physician together
43 voluntarily dismiss the petition.
44 (2) In all cases except those described in subdivision (1) above, the director shall
45 conduct the assessment and may initiate juvenile proceedings and take all
46 other steps authorized by the regular provisions of this Subchapter. If the
47 director decides not to file a petition, the physician, the administrator, or that
48 person's designee may ask the prosecutor Division to review this decision
49 according to the provisions of G.S. 7B-305 and G.S. 7B-306."
50 SECTION 21.(a) G.S. 50-13.10 reads as rewritten:
House Bill 612-Second Edition Page 27

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 "§ 50-13.10. Past due child support vested; not subject to retroactive modification; entitled
2 to full faith and credit.
3 …
4 (d) For purposes of this section, a child support payment or the relevant portion thereof,
5 is not past due, and no arrearage accrues:accrues during the following:
6 (1) From and after the date of the death of the minor child for whose support the
7 payment, or relevant portion, is made;made.
8 (2) From and after the date of the death of the supporting party;party.
9 (3) During any period when the child is living with the supporting party pursuant
10 to a valid court order or to an express or implied written or oral agreement
11 transferring primary custody to the supporting party;party.
12 (4) During any period when the supporting party is incarcerated, is not on work
13 release, and has no resources with which to make the payment.
14 (5) For foster care assistance owed to the State by the supporting party during any
15 period when the child is placed in the custody of a department of social
16 services.
17 …."
18 SECTION 21.(b) Article 9 of Chapter 110 of the General Statutes is amended by
19 adding a new section to read:
20 "§ 110-135.1. Foster care assistance payments.
21 (a) Upon motion in the cause by either party and a showing that the child has been placed
22 in the custody of a department of social services, all of the following shall occur:
23 (1) The obligor's child support obligation, if owed to the State, shall be suspended
24 during any period when the child is placed in the custody of a county
25 department of social services.
26 (2) Any foster care assistance arrears owed to the State for past paid foster care
27 assistance shall be reduced to zero under G.S. 50-13.10.
28 (b) Nothing in this section shall be construed to create a debt owed to the obligor."
29 SECTION 22. Except as otherwise provided, this act becomes effective October 1,
30 2025, and applies to all actions pending or filed on or after that date.
